This was a design-thinking assignment focused on the practical applications of Object Detection and Facial Recognition. 
I brainstormed 5 distinct use cases and developed a technical blueprint for one: an "Automated Attendance System." 
My design outlined the hardware (camera), the preprocessing (grayscale/alignment), and the model (FaceNet/Haar Cascades) needed to identify students in a classroom.

5 Use Cases:
Agriculture: Detecting pests on leaves via drone footage.
Retail: "Self-Checkout" systems that identify groceries without barcodes.
Safety: Detecting if a factory worker is wearing a required helmet.
Medicine: Identifying tumors in X-ray or MRI scans.
Traffic: Counting vehicles at an intersection to optimize light timing.

Learning Outcomes
Real-World Application: Learned to identify high-value problems that can be solved specifically through visual automation.
Solution Architecture: Gained experience in designing a full "end-to-end" system, from data capture to final decision.
Bounding Box Logic: Understood how detection models work by predicting "coordinates" $(x, y, w, h)$ around identified objects.
Ethical Consideration: Developed an awareness of the privacy and bias challenges inherent in facial recognition technology.
